A black box in the car?
US road planners are looking for a source of money to fix the decaying highway system and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of every car.
The devices, which record every kilometre driven and report the information to authorities, are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning agencies to overhaul the antiquated system of funding US roads.
The normally dull field of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colourful alliances.
Libertarians have allied with environmental groups to argue that the government should be able to use the little boxes to record kilometres driven - and possibly where they were driven - and then use the information to calculate tax assessments.
The Tea Party is appalled.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are waiting no longer.
They are currently looking at how they can move to a system where drivers pay per mile driven over the next decade.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
"It's not something we're going to use only potentially," said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans a record of miles driven on all California motorists in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes is going to change.
The technology to do it is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded by the taxes US Americans pay at the pump, is broke.
But people in America are not filling up as much as they used to.
Cars use less petrol.
The state fuel tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 euro cents per litre) has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians dare not raise the tax even one cent when fuel prices are high.
"The gasoline tax is just not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation law expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mileage-based payment system.
"That represents the most viable long-term alternative," he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mileage-based user fee.
Not surprisingly, the idea has appeal to urban liberals because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in ways that reduce congestion and climate-damaging emissions.
California planners are counting on the system in devising strategies to meet the state's ambitious climate change goals, which are enshrined in law.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also said he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free marketers the Reason Foundation also like the idea of making drivers pay by distance travelled.
"It's not a tax that disappears into a black hole," explains Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former US transport ministers, who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move towards mileage-based billing.
The US Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would have covered 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives blocked the move, responding to concerns from rural congressmen who represent people who often have to travel many miles to work or into town in their daily lives.
Several states and major cities are nonetheless moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay mileage fees instead of fuel taxes to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering one.
Illinois is testing it on a limited basis with trucks.
And the I-95 Coalition, which includes the departments of transportation of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently studying how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently fitted with the devices, motorists were sceptical at the thought of the government tracking their every move.
"Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big issue," explains Alauddin Khan, director of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
As the test got underway, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: "It would be relatively easy to turn tachographs into full-blown surveillance devices."
It said there was no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on individuals' daily movements.
Nevada is among a number of states now looking at affordable technology that would allow the state to record miles driven, but not exactly when or where.
This, Khan says, would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some agencies to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company didn't originally set out to help states tax drivers.
Rather, its goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are expected to pay based on the miles they drive.
But the devices she tested are also of interest to road planners because they don't use GPS and provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded," explained Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
Big mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can choose no device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to sell the concept to a wary public by equipping the devices with more features than fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a device for taxation that can also pay parking fees, require insurance to be paid only for miles driven, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which motorists can avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system," a city planning document says.
Some transportation planners, however, wonder if all the talk about pay-per-mile isn't just a giant red herring.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund problem simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-time fee or an annual levy could be imposed on motorists with hybrids or other vehicles that use little gasoline, so they too pay their fair share.
"There's no need for surgery when an aspirin will do just as well," explains Randy Rentschler, the commission's director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will be concerned about their privacy and numerous other things.
Snowden ready to 'cooperate' with Germany on US surveillance
US intelligence whistleblower Edward Snowden has said he is willing to travel to Berlin and testify before the German Bundestag if the US National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander do not provide answers about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met Snowden on Thursday in Russia, where he has been granted asylum, to discuss testifying in Germany.
In a letter from Snowden presented to the media in Berlin on Friday by Ströbele, he writes: "Even though the outcome of my efforts was demonstrably positive, my government continues to treat a dissenting opinion as a breach of trust and seeks to criminalise political expression with the threat of punishment where no defence is possible."
Telling the truth, however, is not a crime.
In the letter, Snowden writes that he is convinced that the support of the international community could convince the US government to drop the charges against him.
The charges brought by the US Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
German Interior Minister Hans-Peter Friedrich told Zeit Online: "If Mr Snowden is willing to talk to German representatives, we will find ways to make that possible."
Relations between the US and Germany have been strained by allegations that the NSA tapped Chancellor Angela Merkel's mobile phone.
Thomas Oppermann, the MP who heads the parliamentary committee responsible for intelligence, said the opportunity should be taken to hear Snowden as a witness if possible "without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the US".
Ströbele, a Green Party MP, posted a picture of himself and Snowden on his Twitter feed.
He was accompanied by two German journalists during his visit to Russia.
Ströbele explained that according to the former NSA employee's lawyer, Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Snowden testifies in Germany, he needs an assurance that he is "safe" there, the MP said.
Snowden states in his letter that he faces a "serious and ongoing" campaign of persecution that has driven him from his home country.
However, he said he was touched by the worldwide reaction to "my act of political expression".
Citizens around the world, as well as high-level politicians - including in the United States - have called the revelations about an unchecked system of extensive surveillance a public service.
In his letter, Snowden makes an offer of cooperation to the German authorities "once the difficulties surrounding the humanitarian situation have been resolved".
Frontier Airlines to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to 100 US dollars to passengers who want to stow hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for a piece of carry-on luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, even though Wednesday's announcement said passengers would be allowed to keep the whole can.
The new charge applies to hand luggage in the overhead bin; small bags under the seat will still be free.
Frontier said it would charge US$25 if the fee was paid in advance and US$100 for travellers who paid at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the US$100 fee was aimed at encouraging travellers to take care of payment in advance.
"We don't want to charge that amount," she explained.
Airlines began charging for the first and second checked bags in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid them therefore stuffed as much as they could in their hand luggage, which meant overhead bins were often overflowing.
Fees are one way to encourage passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee is not really about making money.
It is about Frontier's most loyal customers, who have clearly expressed that it is getting harder and harder to find space in the overhead compartment.
Passengers who buy their tickets on the airline's website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger at Frontier's gate may be allowed to take one piece of luggage for free, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a comparable piece of luggage.
O'Malley said Frontier's website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be aware of the fee before they got to the gate.
Frontier's new hand luggage fee will not come into effect until the summer, with no exact date yet.
Passengers often grumble about baggage surcharges and other fees, but airlines are happy to resort to them.
They argue that transporting luggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they want it.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage fees as a sign that airlines are bringing in enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
Most, however, have so far kept their hands off carry-on baggage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for hand luggage three years ago and was later followed by Allegiant Air, also a low-cost carrier.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungary's Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely follows extra fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the hand luggage fee was generating US$50 million a year for Spirit.
Sorensen, who formerly held an executive position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious what to expect at the gate when passengers were confronted with the company's unusual carry-on fee.
"The boarding process was one of the smoothest I have experienced in my aviation career," he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and hand-wringing discussions at the gate.
"The plane was full," he explained, "and boarding went like clockwork."
Frontier also follows Spirit in charging $2 for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company said passengers who bought lemonade or juice would be allowed to keep the whole can and coffee would be refilled for free.
Water will continue to be free.
US Airways had briefly tried charging for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed it seven months later after passengers complained and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier's move to charge for hand luggage if passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to drive customers to its website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies like Orbitz US$10 to US$25 per ticket sold.
This provides an incentive for all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them rather than through an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, the company began awarding only half as many frequent flyer miles when booking through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, miles were cut again to 25 per cent of the distance flown.
As a result, a Frontier flight booked with a third-party provider for 1,000 miles will earn customers only 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats exclusively by buying directly on Frontier's website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenue fell 9 per cent and flight capacity shrank nearly 13 per cent in the first quarter, according to the financial report released Wednesday by its parent, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has been trying to get a handle on Frontier's finances as part of the sale of the company.
NSA says 'internal error' not hackers to blame for website crash
The shadowy National Security Agency late on Friday said a bug had crippled its public website for several hours and not hackers, as claimed online.
"NSA.gov was down for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update," the spy agency explained in an emailed statement.
It said the problem would be fixed this evening.
It said the claim that the outage was caused by a distributed denial of service (DDoS) attack was not true.
In the early hours of the evening, online server trackers had noticed that the NSA website was down for at least six hours and continues to be down for some users.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson had told ABC News that the agency's sensitive internal network was "in no way" compromised.
Classified information was not at risk, the spokesperson said.
At least one group of hacktivists claimed to have crippled the NSA website with a DDoS attack.
In such attacks, the target website is flooded with page views until the servers are overloaded and the website collapses.
The cyber tactics are relatively simple and the attacks are not designed to penetrate the target system's internal network.
The formerly super-secret NSA, whose nickname was once No Such Agency, now finds itself in the bright light of public scrutiny and facing sharp criticism at home and abroad following revelations in recent months about its extensive surveillance programme - a result of the secret NSA data stolen and published by disillusioned former NSA employee Edward Snowden.
The growing controversy surrounding the intelligence agency fuelled initial speculation that the incident today was the result of a targeted cyber operation.
Bombardier profits fall after drop in shipments and orders
Canadian aircraft and train maker Bombardier Inc reported a 15 per cent drop in net profit on Thursday after being pressured by declining orders and deliveries for aircraft in the third quarter and contract problems in its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft and did not provide any new information on whether the plane would be able to enter commercial service next September according to its ambitious schedule.
The test aircraft's maiden flight a month and a half ago has so far been followed by only three more launches, making it questionable whether the test phase is going as planned.
The results fell short of forecasts and led to a share price drop of more than eight per cent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating from "outperform" to "sector perform" on Thursday, citing limited upside potential for the stock over the next quarter or two.
"While weaker aircraft delivery numbers were widely expected, we are clearly disappointed with the margin performance in transportation," Doerksen said in a note to clients.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the test programme for the aircraft progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more sceptical about the programme.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries aircraft series can catapult the company into the lower end of the market, which is currently dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled to the public in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delays.
But so far, firm orders for the CSeries are moderate at 177, as potential buyers await the results of flight tests and want to see if the company's claims about the new jetliner's fuel efficiency and cost-saving potential are accurate.
There are currently a total of 403 orders and commitments from 15 customers and companies.
Chief executive Pierre Beaudoin says he is confident Bombardier will reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the jet enters commercial service.
Company executives also assured analysts and media on Thursday that the programme was on schedule.
"The test aircraft has not been grounded longer than expected," Beaudoin said on a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates had been scheduled during the aircraft's downtime.
Every manufacturer plans differently.
We decided to do a first flight and then attach a revision period, which we did.
This is done throughout the flight programme.
The second of five test aircraft is expected to take off in the next few weeks, with the rest shortly after, the company said.
Still, analysts remain sceptical about whether the first customer will be able to put a CSeries aircraft into service 12 months after the maiden flight.
Bombardier said it was reviewing its entry-into-service (EIS) planning and would update it in the coming months.
"The slow progress of the flight tests - although apparently in line with Bombardier's internal planning - reinforces our view that entry into service will be delayed until the first quarter of 2015," Doerksen said.
For the third quarter ended Sept. 30, Bombardier's net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents a share, from $172 million, or 9 cents a share, a year earlier.
Adjusted earnings per share were unchanged at 9 cents.
Revenue slipped slightly to $4.1 billion from $4.2 billion.
Analysts had expected earnings of 10 cents a share and revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world's fourth-largest aircraft maker said it delivered 45 planes this quarter, down from 57 last year.
Net orders fell to 26 from 83 aircraft.
The aerospace division's backlog was $32.9 billion as of Sept. 30, unchanged from Dec. 31.
"Aerospace results were in line with our guidance, but the low order intake and overall market conditions were disappointing," Beaudoin said.
Sales in the aerospace division fell 13 per cent to two billion dollars.
Bombardier, the world's largest rail manufacturer, announced that sales in that division rose nearly 11 per cent to $2.1 billion.
The transport division's order book stood at $32.6 billion on 30 September, up slightly from 31 December.
The profit margin in the transport division was affected by settlement problems on some large contracts.
Management said there will be new guidance for the fourth quarter.
Bombardier shares fell 8.5 per cent to 4.83 Canadian dollars in afternoon trading on Thursday, after it was also announced that Google CFO Patrick Pichette will join the board.
Brazil's Embraer SA, the world's third-largest commercial aeroplane maker and Bombardier's closest rival, reported a 10 percent drop in quarterly profit on Thursday.
Cocaine-addicted lawyer who warned drug lord against police investigation faces jail time
Basharat Ditta, 42, passed on information to underworld figure Neil Scarborough
The lawyer was afraid his secret drug addiction would come to light
He was sentenced to three years in prison at Liverpool Crown Court
A well-known criminal lawyer who warned a drug baron he was facing a major police investigation because he was afraid his secret drug addiction would be exposed has been sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, provided underworld figure Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about investigations into his drug trafficking activities after he was compromised by his own cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed "Bash" and praised by criminologists as "first class", was arrested at his home in 2011 after police staked out Scarborough, whom he had represented in an earlier drugs case.
Officers observed Scarborough, 32, deliver three bags of cocaine to the solicitor's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was with colleagues at a bar association dinner.
The investigation revealed that Ditta regularly used class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in his hair, on his wallet and on credit cards.
Over an eight-month period between January and August 2011, he attempted to illicitly obtain information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners.
All four suspects were under police surveillance at the time as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
Along with 32 other people, they were later arrested after police seized £1.5 million worth of heroin and cocaine and £200,000 in cash during a series of house searches.
Ditta, 42, gave information to the criminals because he feared his drug addiction would become public.
Today at Liverpool Crown Court, Ditta, who works for Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn, was found guilty and sentenced on two counts of obstruction of justice after a three-week trial.
He admitted possession of cocaine at an earlier interview.
The lawyer was convicted after police investigating Scarborough discovered he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigating officers followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house and place the drugs, with a purity of 60 per cent, in a black golf glove under the lawyer's dustbin.
Shortly after dropping off the drugs, Scarborough made regular phone calls to Ditta, who was at dinner at Blackburn Rovers' football stadium in Ewood Park.
The lawyer returned home, got the drugs and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
It was revealed in court that Ditta was a "regular user" of cocaine after tests revealed Class A drugs in his hair, wallet and on his credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied using cocaine and said he spoke to the alleged dealer because he was his client, claiming their discussion was subject to "attorney-client privilege".
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were seized and a hair sample was taken from him.
During police questioning, he stated that he operated an office at both his home and work addresses and that clients called him at home for legal matters.
It was revealed in court that he had called key drug trafficking players, some of whom he had previously represented, after significant arrests and informed them of what investigators knew about them.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said, "A criminal lawyer should know better than anyone that you don't break the law."
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal lawyer by getting too involved with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer supplying drugs to his lawyer.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate because he was their lawyer.
But this went far beyond the boundaries of a normal lawyer-client relationship.
He counteracted the police investigation as much as possible so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities.
Mr Ditta thus brought his profession into disrepute.
He was too close to certain clients, particularly Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any wrongdoing, claiming, "If I was a corrupt lawyer, which I'm not, and I wanted to give information to Scarborough, I wouldn't wait 15 hours, I'd do it immediately."
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said: "Mr Ditta took the step from a criminal lawyer to a criminal the moment he started acquiring drugs from organised criminals."
His cocaine addiction led to hopeless compromise and made him susceptible to the motives of leading members of organised crime, who hired him to obtain valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must uphold the highest standards of integrity and inspire trust and confidence in the public.
Ditta betrayed that trust and tried to hide behind the façade of his profession.
Lancashire's Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation into Ditta, which also resulted in a conviction on three counts of possession of cocaine and obstruction of justice, underlining our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We will find you and bring you to justice.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after pleading guilty to conspiracy to traffic heroin, cocaine and cannabis.
Thirty-five other 'persons involved in drug trafficking were sentenced to a total of 153 years for drug offences.
On his website, Ditta posted a Q&A section about himself, stating that his dream job was to represent clients on death row in America as a lawyer, that his ultimate dinner guest was Mohammed Ali and that inequality of opportunity was the motivation for his work.
Kenyan press outraged over controversial media law
