"The bill is draconian and very punitive and we oppose it," said Cyrus Kamau, managing director of Capital Group, which includes CapitalFM, one of Kenya's most respected independent radio stations and news websites.
He said the new media tribunal "will always be biased because it is an extension of the government" and restrictions on content and advertising would damage Kenya's standing in the global economy.
"I hope the president listens to us and we appeal to him to reject this bill and send it back to parliament," he said.
According to The Star newspaper, the government is "effectively putting the media in a stranglehold" through the new law. In contrast, The Standard wrote that democracy and freedom of speech in Kenya had suffered "a severe blow" and dubbed the bill "draconian".
The passage of the bill is one of a series of measures aimed at strengthening national security in the wake of the attacks by armed Islamists on the Westgate shopping mall in September.
The Kenyan media drew the ire of the authorities for publishing security camera footage showing units deployed to the scene allegedly robbing the luxury mall.
Police Commissioner David Kimaiyo responded by summoning two journalists and a leading media figure for questioning, although the summons was withdrawn after an outcry from the media.
Under the new law, media houses can be fined up to 20 million Kenyan shillings and individual journalists up to one million, as well as the further risk of losing their professional recognition or being barred from official press accreditation.
The tribunal also has the right to seize the property of those involved if a fine is not paid.
According to the Daily Nation, "even a single fine can bankrupt most radio stations".
Moreover, the newspaper believes these measures could have a devastating effect on what it describes as Kenya's "vibrant blogosphere".
If they silenced the media, politicians could do whatever they want with impunity.
"No one will ever know," wrote Mutuma Mathiu, a journalist with the Nation, who describes the Kenyan media as a crucial controlling factor in public life.
"Left to their own devices, politicians are leading the country into bankruptcy and us back to the days of hunter-gatherers," he commented.
Kenyan lawmakers have drawn public ire in the past.
In May, they voted to reverse cuts ordered by the National Remuneration Commission and reinstated their hefty salaries of about Sh532,000 tax-free per month - among the highest in the world.
UN announces new poverty reduction goals
The United Nations will begin work immediately on a set of new goals to replace the Millennium Development Goals on poverty reduction announced twelve years ago.
Ahead of the UN Sustainable Development Summit, which began this evening in Rio de Janeiro, Australian diplomats played a key role in the push for "sustainable development goals" to replace the Millennium Development Goals, which expire in 2015.
They were included in the final draft of the document that will be adopted by world leaders, including Ms Gillard, at the summit.
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon told the summit that evening that the time had come to "think beyond national interests".
"I am pleased that member states have agreed to embark on a process to agree universal sustainable development goals," he said.
"These goals will build on our progress from the Millennium Development Goals and form an integral part of the post-2015 development framework.
I will spare no effort to implement this mandate given to me by member states to realise our vision of sustainable development goals that build on the success of the MDGs."
Security concerns grow in Mozambique amid clashes between influential figures
Thousands of people gathered in central Maputo under the watchful eye of the statue of Samora Machel, founder of the state and Mozambique's first president, to chant peace in a rare public demonstration.
"We want peace again, we want stability," said Vanessa de Sousa, managing director of an investment company.
Fearing for the country's future, she swapped her business attire for a T-shirt reading "We demand security" in Portuguese and joined the crowd in the capital's Independence Square on Thursday.
For the past two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, some of the worst fighting since the peace agreement more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement, initially supported by white-ruled Rhodesia and later by the apartheid government of South Africa in an effort to destabilise the country's independent government.
After the 1992 peace agreement, it became an opposition party.
Analysts say it is unlikely that the country will fall back into full-blown conflict, but recent events have worried foreign investors and locals.
The stakes are high for the fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge gas deposits off the coast and coal deposits in the northwest could bring in more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale of Brazil, Eni of Italy and Anadarko of the US.
The ruling Frelimo party, the dominant force since 1975, and Renamo blame each other for the tensions.
Renamo claims that the government provoked the recent clashes by attacking its members in Sofala province, a traditional Renamo stronghold, on 17 October.
The attacks on the former rebels escalated when government troops attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group's leader, Renamo's spokesman told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for the clashes and accuses the organisation of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has tried to play down concerns about instability.
He told AFP, the French news agency, on Wednesday that Dhlakama considered himself a "loser" who "wants to use all his remaining strength to prove that he can impose his decisions on the government".
Both Frelimo and Renamo stress that they want to avoid war.
But concerns have increased since Mazanga was quoted as saying Renamo was abandoning the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the FT that he had meant that Frelimo no longer respected the agreement.
"Our vision is to resume negotiations and to do so seriously," Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to settle tensions fuelled by a series of clashes this year.
"We have two grown men here (Guebuza and Dhlakama) butting heads," says Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and Mozambique expert.
Neither of them is good at negotiating and neither is willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo, which has been pushing for electoral reforms, has already said it will boycott the local elections in November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted the use of violence as an attempt by an ailing movement to extract concessions and financial benefits from the government.
Renamo's electoral success has been shrinking since 1992, while a newer party, the Movimento Democrático de Moçambique (MDM), founded by a former Renamo member, is likely to do better in the elections.
Mazanga claims that Guebuza - whose resignation is due when his second term ends next year - wants to destroy the country's democracy.
"He doesn't want multiparty democracy, he doesn't want transparent elections, he doesn't want peace because he doesn't want to give up the presidency," Mazanga said.
It is unclear what capacity Renamo has, but it has launched unrestful attacks on police stations and vehicles on a key north-south route.
Most of the fighting has taken place in Sofala province, a few hundred kilometres north of Maputo, but home to Beira, the port used by mining companies like Rio Tinto and Vale to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended use of the railway for a month after Renamo announced an attack on the line.
Mazanga responded guardedly when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
Renamo wanted to "warn the international community that things are not good in Mozambique", Mazanga said.
The instability has increased frustration with the government, says Fernando Lima, head of Mediacoop, an independent media company, because many people are already worried about corruption, slow progress on development and a recent wave of kidnappings.
"People think that the government and the president are responsible for the future of the country and he should be the one to find solutions to the problems," he explains.
Omar Sultane, a protester, said people just want stability.
"Nobody cares about Renamo and Frelimo, they just want peace and usable roads again," he explained.
