Drew Bowler, managing director of Bowler Motorsport, explains, "The rally customers who come to Bowler have changed."
They are not all experienced racers, but people looking for excitement, adventure and an accessible route to world-class events.
We are delighted to be able to open up this pathway in partnership with Land Rover and the MSA and believe the format will open up new opportunities to experience the various rally disciplines in the UK and abroad, as well as preparing newcomers for the rigours and reality of Rally Raid.
We've really enjoyed developing the Defender Challenge car - it's going to be an entertaining championship.
In addition, Defender Challenge features a training and test day in February, as well as the option to take part in desert races in North Africa and the Middle East.
Firefighters called to rescue doggy stuck 15 metres above ground on dangerous ledge in quarry
Cocker spaniel dog Ruby had run away after a minor road accident
Three days later she was discovered in her predicament by a walker in the quarry
Firefighters abseiled down a rock face and rescued the dog from certain death.
Firefighters managed to bring a puppy to safety who was stuck on a 15-metre ledge in a rock face.
The nine-month-old cocker spaniel dog, Ruby, had run away after a traffic accident on Sunday afternoon and survived alone for three days before being rescued from a quarry on Wednesday.
Scott Alderson, 25, and his girlfriend Becky Hall, 20, who own the dog, came to Flappit Quarry in Denholme, West Yorkshire, to receive Ruby back and thank firefighters from West Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service.
They had been frantically searching for their missing dog and posting cries for help on social media when she escaped into the quarry after the minor road accident.
At about 2:15pm on Wednesday, a walker walking his dog spotted the stranded Ruby on the 15-metre ledge in the quarry.
Cleckheaton Fire Station's technical rescue team rushed to the scene and abseiled down to rescue Ruby, who was then transported up in a dog crate.
Andy Clayton, technical rescue team specialist, said: "She was in a dangerous position.
She was in the middle of the rock face - 15 metres from the top and the bottom.
She didn't move a muscle during her rescue - she was frozen stiff.
But she is fine now.
She ate some dog biscuits afterwards.
That was a pretty unusual rescue.
The fact that the dog was discovered is incredible.
Peter Lau, technical rescue team specialist, said, "Ruby was very lucky."
There was a possibility that she was very badly injured or worse.
Ruby was taken to the vet for a check-up, but he found nothing other than exhaustion and dehydration.
Becky Hall from Halifax, West Yorkshire, said, "Watching the rescue was scary."
I couldn't believe she was really up there.
It was wonderful to hold her again.
The vet explained that if the exhaustion had become too much and she had collapsed, she probably would have crashed.
The firefighters did a great job.
It was really brave what they did.
We're just so grateful and every one of them was absolutely incredible.
Scott Alderson, from Keighley, added: "We were worried it would fall down but it stayed up."
The firefighters were great.
I can hardly believe where she was.
