George Kerevan: European unbundling gives Scots a choice
A new day, a new horror story on independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is required to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
This provides the cue for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed-wire border along Hadrian's Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde Bill referred to the potential economic benefits that more freedom to travel in the rest of Europe would bring, but - as expected - this played no part in the headlines.
Nor did anyone mention that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more convenient for them.
As Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance would only be a small concession for Brussels in return for what they really want from the Scots.
So not really a story.
And one that is already so outdated that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the "independence means passport controls" canard was at least 40 years ago.
Yet an interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this age-old story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance to the European tune?
Why exchange the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: The grand, post-war plan to unite Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project is officially dead.
All over the EU, parties are gaining ground that are anti-EU or want to jettison the euro as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party - founded only this year - managed to grab almost five million votes in September's federal election, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of Britain's Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is turning out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket into which the respective national economies are forced by adherence to the common currency, many people believe that the European project has gone too far.
The crisis of the euro has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits - that was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has locked its members into exchange rates that are advantageous for German exporters - and German politicians would like to keep it that way.
Without the possibility of devaluing the local currency, Southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage vis-à-vis Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending - spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of Brussels-imposed "green" energy directives - code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage fixes in the world will not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, once the cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and lift Paris to eye level with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving the struggling French economy to struggle.
As a result, Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a crucial by-election, relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the vote - a timely warning to Britain's Labour Party that it cannot assume a split on the right will automatically benefit the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her new-found popularity among white working-class French people?
She wants to use next year's EU elections to forge an anti-EU, anti-Common Currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections - and that is very possible - then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I am trying to make: In the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will coalesce to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something more like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of ingratiating itself with the US.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where does all this leave Scotland?
We can choose to be a region of (in the last resort) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests - which includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can stick where.
I suspect Scotland could do quite well in a looser European union, provided we keep our own currency.
Co-operation with other similar thinking countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider following Norway's lead and retaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is - remarkably - the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 on the basis of rejecting the cuts proposed (and made) by Labour finance minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to have austerity policies imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately signify puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
Early puberty trend is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specialises in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter is already growing breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
Speaking at the American Academy of Pediatrics annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, paediatric endocrinologist Dr Paul Kaplowitz said these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents - it's not usually a sign that puberty is now fast approaching," Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious indicators of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odour, show up earlier in girls.
Yet there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (occurrence of the first menstrual period) over the past 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down slightly from 12.75 in 1970.
"When the breasts start to develop, it's at least two to three years before menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with this Common Problem".
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty is progressing.
It is debatable what actually constitutes the onset of puberty, but it is considered "precocious" if breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates - something a paediatrician can monitor closely.
If it progresses more quickly, tests by an endicronologist might be indicated so that serious problems such as tumours or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatments to delay early menstruation and ward off another consequence: premature ageing of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth retardation and thus small body growth in adults.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the child's age, developmental speed, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication, but he admits: "Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioural problems and girls' feelings of being different from their peers."
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply don't want their very young daughters to have periods.
"They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they will handle the hygiene side," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls one woman whose daughter got her period at ten.
Even though there were early signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and excited because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys, like girls, enter puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz believes the most compelling premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a study in 2001 of girls aged six to nine that linked body fat to the onset of puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, he said, but there are many other factors at play.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards full-blown earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
"We have to be careful how we identify the true onset of puberty," said Dr Lawrence Silverman, a paediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their paediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who blossom early need reassurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it comes earlier than expected.
Jumbo manufacturers clash over seat width in face of big orders
A dispute has erupted between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of tourist class seats on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a bitter clash at the Dubai Airshow this month.
The dispute revolves around the width of seats offered to passengers in tourist class on long flights - not always the ones airlines care most about, but this designated space is key to efficiency claims on the latest aircraft from Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week called for an industry standard requiring a seat width of at least 46 cm (18 inches) in coach class, but US arch-rival Boeing says that should be up to airlines.
The dispute comes at a time when plane makers are vying to sell even bigger versions of their twin-engine long-haul planes and are expecting record orders at the 17-21 November event.
How the rear of the aircraft is designed - in particular whether there are rows of nine or ten seats - is critical to the stated economic results that the new "mini-jumbo" design is expected to deliver.
Boeing claims its modernised "777X" holds 406 people with coach class seats that are over 17 inches wide, allowing ten per row.
Airbus says its rival version of the A350 carries 350 people in 18-inch-wide coach class seats, with nine per row.
Aircraft giants often dish out blows over technical details via advertisements in the trade press.
Now Airbus is appealing directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to make the running with more than 100 orders.
Recently, the company unveiled an ad that could be the start of a new ad war, showing backers a picture of three people sitting squeezed together in a restaurant, accompanied by the caption: "Would you accept this?"
"Boeing is proposing long-haul flights in seats tighter than regional turbo-props," says Airbus sales chief John Leahy.
People are getting fatter in the face of changing diets, but aircraft seats have not changed radically.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 defined modern long-haul travel, and the end of the century, the weight of the average American male between the ages of 40 and 49 has increased by 10 per cent, according to data from the US Department of Health and Human Services.
The waist circumference of the average American male in the 21st century is 100.8 cm, according to US health statistics.
Airbus says its rival is sticking to a seating concept from the 1950s, when the average girth of the newly christened "jet set" was narrower.
Airbus says it has conducted research that proves an extra inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases sleep quality by 53 per cent.
Boeing disputes Airbus' figures on seat dimensions, saying it is not at the discretion of manufacturers to decide how airlines balance fares and furnishings.
The company also says research shows the experience on the plane depends on more than seat width.
"It really boils down to giving airlines flexibility to do what they think they need to do to be successful," explains Boeing flight cabin expert Kent Craver.
They don't want us to dictate what makes them profitable.
They know their business better than anyone else.
For passengers, it's about more elbow room, but for manufacturers, it's increasingly an issue that can affect sales.
Behind the dispute is a race for aircraft orders estimated to be worth at least $700 billion by list price over the coming decades, which could have a lasting impact on the export balance of the US or Europe.
As Reuters first reported in July, seat layout is the driving force behind the dispute over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 per cent more efficiency per seat on their latest twin-engine long-haul designs than the market leader in the segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing's claims about the results depend in part on comparing the 777X, with its ten seats per row, to the original design of nine seats on the 777.
The increased unit cost is still less than the ten seats per row aircraft currently in use.
"Boeing is therefore squeezing more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive with our products," says Kevin Keniston, head of passenger comfort at European Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say full cabins of ten seats per row on existing 777s suggest many passengers opted for the narrower layout, which could come with cheaper fares.
"Eighteen inches of seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is: from an economic standpoint, the Airbus offering is driven by the threat of the 777," says Mary Kirby, cabin interior design expert and founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The globetrotting jet salesmen even carry tape measures to re-measure the furnishings on their competitors.
Even as they tout comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with high-density layouts for budget airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seat rows, but says it has not yet sold one.
Until recently, Airbus stressed the importance of more cabin customisability and offered wide aisle seats on some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets, experts say calls for a new industry standard are likely to fall flat but could distract from the wave of 777X sales.
New anti-nicotine vaccine could put an end to smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could kill the pleasure of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
More trials are needed before human testing, which could take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results were good.
"We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy may one day help millions of smokers who have tried to quit, trying all the methods available on the market, but have experienced that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches," Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information to produce nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then produce a steady stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt down nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralise them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from experiencing a nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal activity levels.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, took a "time-out", the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccines had to be given so frequently to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, if a future human vaccine was completely safe, it could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, however, smokers would use it to quit.
"They then know that when they start smoking again, they no longer feel pleasure from it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them kick the habit," he explained.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but at the same time warned that more research was needed.
Tripodi denies being influenced by Obeid
Former New South Wales Labor Party Minister Joe Tripodi is under investigation by the state's corruption watchdog.
The former NSW minister denies changing maritime leasing regulations at the request of his political mentor Eddie Obeid, who had hidden interests in three properties on state-controlled land.
The Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC Independent Commission) on Friday widened its investigation into whether Obeid lobbied various state ministers to renew leases at Circular Quay, where the Obeids operated two restaurants and a café, without tendering after they expired in August 2005.
Now an investigation is underway into allegations that Tripodi knew of Obeid's covert interest in the properties, after Tripodi's former deputy chief of staff Lynne Ashpole testified to that effect on Thursday.
In years of talks that began in 2005, the government had pushed for public tenders for the leases.
The leaseholders were against this and also wanted longer terms.
In 2009, the leases for the Circular Quay businesses, which earned the Obeids $2.5 million a year, were renewed without public tender.
Tripodi, who was ports minister from February 2006 to November 2009, had originally supported public tendering.
But he denied making the changes at the request of Obeid, who Tripodi confirmed had been pushing for a revamp of the government's leasing arrangements.
A telephone transcript provided to ICAC showed conversations from August and September 2007 between Obeid, Tripodi and Steve Dunn, a senior civil servant who had moved to the ports ministry after working under Obeid at the Fisheries Department.
"Was the topic discussed in those phone conversations the drafting of the commercial leasing regulations?" deputy commissioner Anthony Whealy asked Tripodi.
"No," Tripodi replied.
I can't remember what was discussed, but it definitely wasn't.
Definitely not between me and Mr Obeid.
Israeli fighter jets attack target in Syria, official sources say
