At least twice already this year, Israel has carried out air strikes on missile deliveries in Syria.
Foreign workers on 457 visas could be subjected to 'authenticity test'
The government is considering an "authenticity test" for foreign workers on 457 visas as part of expanded measures.
If introduced, the test would be applied through a criterion designed to prevent the 457 from being used to fill unskilled jobs or as a backdoor way for family and friends to move to Australia.
A government discussion draft was released today after former Labor Party MP Maxine McKew condemned the government's comments regarding foreign workers because they could be taken as an insult by Australia's neighbours.
"Loud statements like 'foreigners should get in line' and 'hire Australians first' are a very unpleasant throwback to the days when unions demanded a protected labour market," she told Australia India Institute today.
Historically, that meant white workers should be protected - and if some in the region heard echoes of that historical artefact, I wouldn't be surprised.
The discussion proposal outlines twelve measures once mooted by former Immigration Minister Chris Bowen.
Immigration Minister Brendan O'Connor, who was in Sri Lanka yesterday for talks on people smuggling, has implemented five of the recommended changes, with the others still under consideration.
If the "genuineness criterion" is adopted, then someone applying for a visa could be screened to see if "the application is genuine in cases where the applicant is related or personally connected to the owner or relevant person of the sponsoring company."
Companies could also be required to account for the number of 457 visa holders, after companies in the past that initially wanted to support only a small number of workers ended up hiring hundreds.
Meanwhile, a 35-year-old Sri Lankan asylum seeker is believed to have died of a heart attack after arriving on Christmas Island in a refugee boat this week.
The man's distraught nine-year-old son, who had come to Australia with him, has been cared for since his father's death on Wednesday by an adult cousin who was also on the boat.
Australian authorities took the man to Christmas Island Hospital, where he died.
A study has been announced by the UK government to increase the benefits of the HS2 rail project for Scotland.
The work by HS2 Ltd proposes to deliver high-speed links between Scotland and the north of England as early as the start of Phase 1 in 2026.
Transport Minister Baroness Kramer said the project "will bring Britain closer together".
Scottish Transport Minister Keith Brown said he was delighted to be working with the UK Government on the plan.
Phase 1 consists of a new high-speed rail link between London and the West Midlands.
Once Phase 2 is completed, there will be links to Manchester and Leeds.
In June, the government revised the estimated cost of building the high-speed rail link between London and the north of England from £32.7 billion to £42.6 billion.
The UK government, which is in talks with Transport Scotland, has asked HS2 Ltd to look at further route capacity and journey time improvements for the north of England and Scotland.
This includes the possibility of an eventual journey time of three hours or less from Glasgow and Edinburgh to London.
Baroness Kramer said, "Our aim for HS2 is a truly national route network that brings Britain and its cities closer together."
We are going ahead with HS2 because it brings huge benefits.
Without it we face a capacity crisis on our rail network.
But it's also about the connectivity between 18 UK cities, including Glasgow and Edinburgh, which will be improved thanks to HS2.
Scottish Secretary Alistair Carmichael commented: "Today's announcement is good news for Scotland."
Speaking on behalf of the Scottish Government, Keith Brown urged Carmichael to be "unequivocal" in his commitment to Scottish inclusion on the HS2 network.
Brown said, "The high-speed rail link holds the potential of huge economic benefits for Scotland, but at the same time Scotland's economic strength provides a case for fast rail links across the UK."
That's why we are delighted to be working as a partner with the UK Government to explore options for a high speed rail link in Scotland that will create benefits for all and complement the Glasgow-Edinburgh link that the Scottish Government is already planning.
I look forward to considering the enquiry report with UK Ministers next year and deciding together on the next steps.
Rules on electronic devices on planes remain in force in Australia for now
Australian airline passengers will still have to switch off tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing, despite efforts in the US to relax regulations on such devices.
The US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allows US airlines to change their requirements so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during critical phases of flight, as long as they are in "flight mode".
Passengers are already allowed to do this during most of the flight, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian airlines are monitoring the decision, which US airlines will have to do reams of work to implement, but have no immediate plans to change their rules.
The air navigation service provider CASA also said it would look at the announcement, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical phases of flight still apply in Australia.
"CASA currently has no specific regulations regarding the use of electronic devices on aircraft," it was announced.
The issue is subject to regulations requiring airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to follow safety instructions given by cabin crew.
Virgin has already held talks with CASA about expanding the use of its Wi-Fi entertainment system on flights and said it was open to changes, but they would have to be initiated by lawmakers.
