The FAA regulations apply to US airlines.
However, we are always interested in developments in regulations that can benefit passengers and will certainly take a close look at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it.
The decision affects US airlines differently depending on the age of their fleet.
They will have to demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from mobile devices, and change manuals, training materials, carry-on programmes and customer education.
"After confirming its fleet's tolerance, an airline may allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any altitude," the FAA announced.
In rare cases of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off devices during landing.
The group also recommended that heavier devices be securely stowed under the seat or in compartments above the seats during take-off and landing.
Pawnshops boom in Singapore as crisis hits middle class
At a pawnshop in Singapore's Bendemeer shopping centre, Janani Amirthalinga trades a gold bangle, a ring and a pair of earrings to help pay her daughters' school fees.
"My husband and I just bought a house, that's where all my money is," says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) every month as an administrative assistant and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, such is the demand in parts of Southeast Asia - where household debt is increasing - that ValueMax, where she made her exchange, this week became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
Pawning jewellery is not only a quick way to get money - 1,300 Singapore dollars in Janani Amirthalinga's case - but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an APR of 17 per cent, just above the 15.4 per cent charged by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
Pawnshops, however, offer the advantage that no credit checks or income verification are required here, which is why loans can be obtained more quickly than from banks.
This is why millions of people in the region are turning to pawnshops after families feel the pressure of rising living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit due to loose fiscal policies in developed economies, lower and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to help make up the difference as the economy sputters.
This week, ratings agency Standard & Poor's called growing household debt, mainly from rising mortgages, a risk factor for Asian banks' creditworthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt to GDP ratios in Asia, according to the agency.
Malaysia tops the list at 80 per cent of GDP, an increase from 60 per cent as recently as 2008.
Economists are also worried about high consumer debt in Thailand, which narrowly emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, data showed continued weakness in exports and a slowdown in consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (of the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," said Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have added to the trend of pawning personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewellery into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 per cent of pawned items in the city-state's 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
Thailand's largest pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 per cent increase in customers at its branches in recent months.
Growth in the pawn business has been so strong that ValueMax, operator of the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, is looking to expand not only into neighbouring Malaysia - where it operates four houses - but also outside Asia, said Yeah Lee Ching, ValueMax's managing director.
The company is funding that with 60 per cent of the $66 million it raised in its Singapore IPO this week.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire over high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly increase debt.
"Customers are borrowing items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables does not increase household debt," she explains.
Pawnbroking is increasingly socially accepted as short-term, secured finance.
Also, not all people who use pawnshops are in financial difficulty.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax branches to pawn gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
"They include the wealthy who need to borrow for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses that need to bridge cash flow shortages," Yeah says.
Sometimes they also just need money very quickly.
Rescue package of 325 million Australian dollars for Tasmanian health system
The Australian government is insisting on the tough conditions attached to the 325 million Australian dollar bailout package for the Tasmanian health system to ensure the state government cannot squander the money.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek has announced the Commonwealth will take "immediate action" to avert a crisis caused by an ageing population in the island nation, higher rates of chronic illness and system constraints.
The funding for a four-year period was agreed after government consultations with Independent Tasmanian MP Andrew Wilkie.
"The government has put together an emergency recovery package that we believe addresses the unique challenges facing the state," Plibersek said today.
The $325 million package includes $31 million in emergency assistance for elective services.
Another 2600 operations, including orthopaedic surgery and treatment for cataracts, will eliminate backlogs.
There is also money for day hospitals in Hobart and Launceston, better follow-up after inpatient stays, specialist training, mental health services and the introduction of an electronic health record system in local hospitals.
"These investments are in line with ideas that concerned hospital staff have told me are the best way to improve the Tasmanian health system," Tanya Plibersek said.
The Minister insisted on strict reporting and accountability from the Tasmanian Government.
The state must maintain current funding levels to be able to receive money from the Commonwealth and report monthly on where the extra money has been spent, she said.
A three-member commission will be set up to ensure the state delivers health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie explained today, the $325 million would be of little use if "it is not accompanied by real reforms that put Tasmania's public health system on a more sustainable course."
Notwithstanding, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent assistance, which he first expressed to the Prime Minister in early May.
"I am confident that the federal aid will go a long way in taking the state's public health system off the worry list," Wilkie said.
According to the state government, these elective benefits will largely make up for recent cuts.
But federal opposition health spokesperson Peter Dutton believes today's announcement is only a "band-aid solution".
"We are in the position we are in today because the Labor state government has taken $430 million out of the health system," he told ABC TV.
It can't be that a state government rips almost half a billion dollars out of the system and the Commonwealth puts 300 million into it and then pretends it's good news, he said.
Dutton called on Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the bailout would be spent on additional bureaucracy.
Guillaume Nicloux's adaptation of Denis Diderot's novel is convincing with exceptional production design and period detail, but it is also heavier fare than necessary.
Set in 1760s France, the plot tells the poignant story of Suzanne, a young noblewoman who is sent to a convent by her family.
When she rebels, she is confronted with the extreme cruelty of an extremely sadistic superior and becomes the object of erotic fascination for another.
The film never slips into prurience or sensationalism - and therein lies its problem.
The solemn seriousness with which the film is told also makes it a torturous penitential shirt for the audience.
Syria has destroyed its ability to manufacture chemical weapons, says monitoring group
Syria has destroyed key chemical weapons and gitft gas munitions manufacturing facilities, the global chemical weapons monitoring group said on Thursday, while heavy clashes broke out in the north of the country near one of the sites where suspected toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the civil war began almost three years ago.
The announcement by the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came a day before the deadline on
1 November deadline set by the Hague-based organisation for Damascus to destroy or render "inoperable" all chemical weapons production facilities, including all machines for mixing chemicals into poison gas and filling munitions.
The completion of this operation, which is essentially the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all of Syria's chemical weapons by mid-2014.
Destroying the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus still needs to start destroying the existing weapons and stockpiles.
There are believed to be about 1,000 tonnes of chemicals and weapons in the country, which includes mustard gas and the nerve agent sarin.
The announcement came at a time of fighting on Thursday in the town of Safira, where experts say there is a chemical weapons production facility as well as storage sites, according to the Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
The activist group, which tracks the death toll through a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday 120,296 people had died.
Of those, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children, it said.
On the government side, 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad's army, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 were Lebanese Hezbollah militants.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On 25 July, the UN estimated the number of dead in the conflict since March 2011 at 100,000.
This figure has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad's troops have been fighting the rebels, many of whom have links to al-Qaida groups, in Safira for weeks.
The Observatory said there were casualties on both sides on Thursday, but gave no details.
The fighting underscores the danger facing chemical weapons inspectors as their mission to rid Syria of its toxic arsenal is a race against time amid a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team "is now satisfied that it has seen all the major production and mixing/filling facilities cited by Syria and witnessed their destruction."
Therefore, "no further inspection activities are planned at this time."
Earlier this week, inspectors had said they had completed the first round of verifications, visiting 21 of 23 sites cited by Damascus.
Due to security concerns, the visit of two facilities was not possible, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPWC said the two sites had been "abandoned ... according to the Syrian statement ... and the chemical weapons programme items present there had been relocated to other named facilities that were inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the Safira site was one of the two facilities that OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has submitted a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC's executive committee next month.
"I take my hat off to the bravery and courage you all have shown in completing the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organisation," Ahmed Uzumcu, the monitoring agency's director-general, said in comments published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting Assad's government and its security forces in this civil war, which includes many members of the Alawites, a breakaway from Shia Islam.
Looking at further developments, the head of the monitoring group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there had been a powerful explosion at an air defence facility in Syria's coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
The cause of the explosion was not known, he said.
Anger over verdict for Bali bomber
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people killed in the 2002 Bali bombing reacted angrily to the verdict for the last of the instigators to be tried, as they believe Umar Patek should be summarily shot.
Patek, who spent nearly ten years on the run as one of Southeast Asia's most wanted persons, was sentenced yesterday to 20 years in prison for his role in building explosive devices for the bombing.
With suspended sentences, he could be released after 15 years.
The 45-year-old was found guilty of mass murder for the attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist district of Kuta that killed 202 people, including 88 Australians, and injured many more.
A guilty verdict was also reached on a number of terrorism-related charges, which included a wave of bomb attacks on churches in Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
Prosecutors had sought a life sentence, although they could have sought the death penalty for the man, who is also known as the "Demolition Man" because of his reputation as a master bomb maker.
The decision has brought back painful memories for June Corteen, a Perth mother who lost her 39-year-old twin daughters Jane and Jenny in the devastation wrought by Patek and his co-conspirators almost a decade ago.
Fighting back tears, she said Patek should have been sentenced to death.
I really mean he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
"He should be put in front of a firing squad," Corteen told AAP.
I have to live every day with the fact that I won't have any more grandchildren and I will never see my daughters again.
The Sari Club was razed to the ground when a massive bomb exploded in a pick-up truck parked outside the nightclub shortly after 11pm on 12 October 2002.
Peter Hughes was in Paddy's Bar, where just 20 seconds earlier a suicide bomber detonated a backpack filled with explosives.
He fell into a coma for a month after the attack and "died" three times while on life support.
Hughes said Patek deserved the same fate as the three other members of the Jemaah Islamiah terror cell - Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samudra - who were responsible for the carnage and executed four years ago.
Really, this guy should get the death penalty before anyone else.
To let him live - no, there is no reason to let him live.
Getting 20 years after killing 202 people and injuring many hundreds is not much.
Patek is the last of the Bali bombers to stand trial.
He eluded capture for nearly a decade but was finally apprehended in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where US forces killed former al-Qaida chief Osama bin Laden barely four months later.
During the trial, an FBI agent testified that intelligence reports had indicated that Patek was in Pakistan to meet bin Laden with the aim of rebuilding the link between Southeast Asian terror groups and al-Qaida.
"He did not turn himself in," Corteen said.
Until recently, he has shown no remorse for how much suffering he caused others.
The verdict came ahead of the tenth anniversary of the attack this year, which will be marked with commemorations in Bali and Australia.
"There will be a lot of tears this year," Corteen said.
Patek can still appeal his sentence.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on planes (but not make mobile phone calls)
Air travellers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play games, listen to music and watch movies from take-off to landing, but not make cellphone calls, according to new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the US on Thursday.
But passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented would depend on the airline in question, FAA official Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated flight crew training manuals and equipment stowage rules to reflect the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on aircraft.
Among those airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not allowed to restart them until the plane reaches an altitude of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the approach, passengers must turn them off again and are not allowed to restart them until the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices during takeoff, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other planes that have been retrofitted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Flight Attendants Association, welcomed the changes.
"When the new regulation is safely implemented - and we are working closely with the airline on this - both sides will benefit," Glading commented.
We are frankly tired of feeling like watchdogs on this issue.
However, internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, texting or downloading data under three kilometres remain prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave an American Airlines jet in public view because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops must still be stowed, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
In-flight mobile phone calls also remain prohibited.
Regulatory authority for phone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, safety expert on national transportation issues told CBS News mobile phones are still considered a risk.
"Cell phones are really a concern, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that airborne transmission can also interfere with transmission towers," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to study the issue recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has mounted on the FAA to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri argue that there are no valid safety reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies report that up to one-third of passengers forget or ignore to turn off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travellers in 1966 after reports of interference with navigation and communications equipment from FM radios carried by passengers, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and FAA-approved to be unaffected by electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers once they reach cruising altitude for a number of years.
Fliers adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger planes should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit minimal radiation when you turn pages.
But transmission levels are stronger when downloading or sending data.
Among the advocates of relaxing restrictions on device use by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to determine problems, but could find none.
Members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of device use.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed the disruption from the devices was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports from pilots of aircraft systems being disrupted by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off the devices during instrument landings in poor visibility.
A travel industry group welcomed the changes, calling them a reasonable adjustment for travellers who would be extensively equipped with technology today.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognises that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
Bird rescued by air rescue service from North Sea drilling island released
A bird flown to shore by air ambulance after being found exhausted on a North Sea drilling island has been released back into the wild.
The water rail was flown by helicopter to Aberdeen last month, where it was nursed by the Scottish SPCA at its rescue centre in Alloa.
Colin Seddon, head of the centre, said: "This water rail was probably a winter migrant from northern Europe, held up by the strong winds over the North Sea."
Apparently, the exhausted bird sought refuge on the oil rig.
He added: "It was unable to fly any further, so we were contacted for help."
On its release, the water rail was fit and well again.
Is Europe's elite ready to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing business to the table and defining what those who deliver prosperity and jobs in Britain want to change about our relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders, asking them what they think about Britain, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed over 1,000 business leaders, roughly representing UK business sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses now export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing, while those in the EU are stagnating.
They would like to see new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil favoured from the government side, rather than being bogged down with the long and arduous process of reforming the obscure EU institutions.
Asked for their views on certain statutory issues - from anti-trust to product legislation - the majority of business leaders believe control over these key powers should be brought back to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, as businesses said the costs of Brussels regulations now outweighed the benefits of being part of Europe's trading zone - even 40 per cent of large companies agreed, traditionally the most pro-European.
Finally, and probably most telling, our survey of business leaders found that a clear majority want the UK to chart a course towards changing the deal, and to have a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This finding, found among businesses of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that business is pushing for "meaningful change" that brings the reins of power back to the UK.
The stakes are high - a change to the deal and better terms for Britain would see 16 per cent change their minds in favour of staying in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should have no doubts: This poll shows that British business is behind his plan for renegotiating Britain's terms for EU membership.
It also shows that businesses expect a renegotiation to significantly shift the balance of power back to the UK.
A better deal for the UK economy is possible and increasingly necessary now that the Eurozone is moving towards closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the result of our survey shows, which for businesses means an increased focus on trade and a fundamental shift in Brussels' approach to regulations.
Gazprom's Alexei Miller calls pipeline in Bulgaria the start of a new gas era
The start of construction of the South Stream pipeline in Bulgaria represents the launch of one of Europe's largest energy projects, the Gazprom executive said.
"Today's event is a milestone: construction work has started on the Bulgarian section of the South Stream gas pipeline, the largest and most important project in Europe," Gazprom CEO Alexei Miller said in a statement on Thursday.
The project is a key element for the energy security of the entire European continent.
South Stream is intended to provide more diversity in Russia's export routes through Europe.
A contract dispute between Gazprom and its counterparts in Ukraine, where most of Russia's gas for Europe is stored, is causing increased risk on conventional routes, officials said.
Miller said the direct connection to Bulgaria, a member of the European Union, meant the geopolitical risks associated with transit countries were eliminated "forever".
Bulgarian consumers will receive gas from South Stream at discounted rates when the entire project comes on stream in 2015.
Gazprom says construction in other downstream countries on the planned route will begin by the end of the year.
The pipeline is designed for an annual capacity of 62.3 billion cubic metres of natural gas.
