Royal Commission hearing: two YMCA workers charged with sex offences ahead of allegations against Jonathan Lord
Two New South Wales (NSW) YMCA staff had been charged with child sex offences before allegations were made against Caringbah children's nurse Jonathan Lord in 2011, the Royal Commission into Child Sexual Abuse has heard.
But in its opening statement to the commission, the YMCA had said it had "never been involved in any incident of child sexual abuse in the organisation".
Executive Director Phillip Hare was asked about a case in which a YMCA employee had been charged with offences involving child pornography, and another in which a YMCA Caringbah Hall PE teacher had been convicted of abusing children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, a lawyer assisting the commission, that he had known about the first case but was unaware of the second.
He acknowledged the YMCA's opening statement to the commission was also inaccurate in claiming "there have been external reviews of the YMCA in which the YMCA has been recognised as being at the forefront of child safety".
Evidence before the commission instead shows that the YMCA was informed that it had received the second lowest rating out of a possible four in a Department of Education and Communities quality audit in August that year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that management had failed "from me down" in hiring Lord and had not ensured that staff were aware of their obligations to report breaches of child safety policies.
Lord had been convicted earlier this year of sex offences against 12 boys during his two years working for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
But Hare denied that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented staff from reporting Lord's child safety violations.
Staff testified they observed violations including Lord being alone with children, babysitting them privately, letting them sit on his lap, saying to one that he loved it, and letting children play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who had asked for child protection training because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that children's services manager Jacqui Barnat, who was Lord's supervisor at the Caringbah YMCA, "was very intimidating and very aloof most of the time".
The manager said he would not accept statements from staff that they had been afraid to report to their supervisors.
Instead, he said, their friendship with Lord rather affected their judgement, which is why they did not report him.
Hare said he had shared with the YMCA NSW board his view that the lesson the organisation needed to learn from the "Jonathan Lord incident" was "not about reporting" by staff, and the board had agreed with him.
Hare said the decision to push staff to sign confidentiality pledges shortly after the allegations arose was made by the YMCA's executive director of children's services, Liam Whitley.
He said this was to prevent contamination of evidence, but was "overzealous" and poorly implemented.
YMCA NSW was not a safe organisation for children during the time Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Griffith University professor Stephen Smallbone, an expert on child sexual abuse, told the commission.
He explained that there had been "serious problems" in the recruitment, vetting, induction, training and supervision of staff.
The hearing was adjourned until 20 December.
Tony Blair said he would jump at the chance to return as British Prime Minister - but admits a comeback is unlikely.
In an interview this evening to mark the fifth anniversary of his departure from office, the 59-year-old revealed his views on a range of domestic issues.
Since stepping down in June 2007 after a decade as head of state, Blair has largely avoided commenting on British politics, mostly confining his comments to foreign policy and his role as envoy to the Quartet of Middle East peacemakers.
Asked if he would like to return to the post of prime minister, Blair was quoted by the Evening Standard from London as saying, "Yes, certainly, but it's unlikely to happen, so ..."
As horse show pundits flocked to Cardiff to choose the Horse of the Year, they were aware that a tough competition lay ahead.
But none were prepared for three-year-old Fenton Kirkland.
The toddler, who is not even in kindergarten and only took his first steps a few months ago, and his Shetland pony Toffee trotted easily through the three rounds to take the first prize - leaving 30 adult opponents behind.
The inseparable pair, both the same size, were praised for their appearance, behaviour and style at the annual competition, organised by Sunnybank Equestrian Centre in Rudry, near Cardiff.
Competing against men and women with elegant bowler hats, he had his plate cap on at a cheeky angle and led the two-year-old Toffee around the ring.
Fenton was praised by the judges for his natural pony handling skills, which were far above his age.
And Toffee received top marks for his appearance and personality.
Fenton had received Toffee as a gift for his third birthday last March and had practised with the Shetland pony every day since.
His mother, Donna, 30, said, "Fenton and Toffee are a great pair."
They had to compete against the entire field and walked off the course with a gold trophy and rosette.
It was only the second time he'd competed with Toffee and we were all thrilled when he won.
Complete strangers in the arena thought he was so phenomenal that they wanted to be photographed with him.
The little boy from the village of Nantyglo, near Ebbw Vale, South Wales, is following in the footsteps of his aunt Sharon Howells, who has been showing horses for over ten years.
Howells told us, "The whole audience was electrified and everyone was cheering and clapping for him."
He walked the length of the arena on sand and although he looked so tiny, he did a fantastic job.
Fenton is crazy about animals - he loves horses, tractors and farms and has two chickens he looks after.
The way he has started, it won't be long before he is at the Horse of the Year Show - and I am sure he will do well."
A spokesman for the annual horse show said, "Fenton is only three, but he knows how to handle his pony."
Together they make a great team.
The judges scored Fenton and Toffee on how well they did and presented themselves in the show ring.
They look for good teamwork between pony and handler - and there Fenton and Toffee were the best in the ring.
I'm sure Fenton's cute clothes played their part, it really suited the occasion perfectly.
Chinese newspaper to be 'reformed' after appeal
A Chinese newspaper that had called for the release of a reporter charged with defamation on its front page should be reformed, a press regulator has said.
The Guangzhou-based New Express had printed a rare public call for the release of journalist Chen Yongzhou.
But Chen later admitted on television that he had accepted bribes to falsify reports about a partly state-owned company.
Now the New Express is undergoing a "comprehensive rectification", the regulator said.
The "rectification order" was issued by the Guangdong Bureau of Press and Publications, Radio, Film and Television.
Preliminary investigations revealed that the New Express, which is part of the Yangcheng Evening News Group, had published several inaccurate reports about Zoomlion, a listed company, between September 2012 and August 2013.
"The editorial management of the New Express was disorderly," the regulator announced in a statement.
It said it had decided to "impose an administrative penalty on Chen Yongzhou and revoke his reporter's licence".
It also said it had "ordered the Yangcheng Evening News Group to conduct a full rectification of the New Express and recommended that it identify the relevant responsible persons at the New Express and immediately review the New Express' management team."
Chen had written several articles for the New Express reporting alleged financial irregularities at a construction equipment manufacturer called Zoomlion.
After he was arrested, the newspaper published two front-page appeals for his release and backed his journalistic work.
But then Chen appeared on state television and admitted that he had published false reports for pay.
"In this case, I have damaged Zoomlion as well as the entire news industry and its ability to gain the trust of the public," he told state news channel CCTV.
I did it primarily because I was after money and fame.
I have realised that I did wrong.
Following Chen's apology, the New Express published a front-page apology, saying they had failed to properly verify the reports.
Several high-profile suspects have made confessions on television recently.
Experts say confessions are still routinely coerced, despite a change in the law earlier this year prohibiting authorities from forcing anyone to incriminate themselves.
Drug tunnel with its own railway discovered between the USA and Mexico
One of the most sophisticated tunnels used for drug smuggling between the US and Mexico, complete with lighting, ventilation and electric rail service, has now been discovered.
The US authorities described the tunnel, measuring 120 by 90 centimetres, as one of the most sophisticated passages they had ever found.
The tunnel, which runs in a zigzag pattern over a length of nearly six football fields, connects warehouses near Tijuana, Mexico, and San Diego, USA.
There are countless inconspicuous warehouses in the area, making it easier to conceal trucks loaded with drugs.
The tunnel was closed before drugs could be transported undetected in it, authorities said.
Eight and a half tonnes of marijuana and 148 kilogrammes of cocaine were seized when the tunnel was discovered, court records show.
Three men, who authorities said worked as drivers, were charged with possession and intent to sell marijuana and cocaine.
They face prison sentences ranging from ten years to life if found guilty.
In Nogales, Arizona, smugglers rely on an extensive underground network of drainage tunnels.
The tunnel is the eighth major passage discovered in San Diego since 2006.
Some of the largest tunnels were discovered after the October marijuana harvest in central Mexico, challenging the drug cartels on how to get their product to consumers quickly.
In 2010, authorities found a nearly 640-metre passage with tracks running from a kitchen in a Tijuana apartment building to two warehouses in San Diego.
British police serve Assange with extradition warrant
British police today served an extradition warrant on WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange, who has sought refuge and asylum at the Ecuadorian embassy in London.
Scotland Yard said it had served the 40-year-old Australian with a "notice to surrender" requiring him to appear at a police station, adding that if he failed to comply he would face arrest.
Assange faces extradition to Sweden on sex offence charges after exhausting his options under British law since the Supreme Court rejected his appeal against extradition earlier this month.
Fearing Stockholm would extradite him to the US, he had sought refuge at the Ecuadorian embassy in London on 19 June, asking the South American country for political asylum.
Scotland Yard had served "a 40-year-old man with a notice to present himself at a police station at a time of our choosing", a spokesman said.
He continues to breach conditions of his release on bail.
The embassy had no comment on the service of the police summons.
Assange fears he will be extradited from Sweden to the United States to face possible espionage charges after publishing more than 250,000 diplomatic messages on the disclosure website WikiLeaks.
Driver who sped at 210 km/h with hot drink between legs fined £1,000
A motorist has been fined £1,000 for driving at up to 210mph with a hot drink between his legs.
Andrew Howie, 35, of Tiptree, Essex, was stopped in his Mercedes Benz on the A120 near Braintree on 27 May.
After police pulled him over, they discovered the drinks cup between his legs.
At Colchester Magistrates' Court Howie pleaded guilty to driving without due care and attention.
He was given seven points and banned from driving for six months.
Howie was also ordered to pay £90 costs and a £100 victim surcharge.
Tax for foreign property owners against London's speculation bubble
The Treasury has provisionally costed through the CGT measure, but is still awaiting a final decision from Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne, who imposed a 7% stamp duty on homes costing over £2 million in the 2012 budget, as well as annual charges for buyers holding homes as a company rather than as individuals.
