Prices in Central London showed steady annual growth of 5.6%, but were overshadowed by a burgeoning 'domestic' market, with the south-west, north (7.4%) and east (6.5%) of the city experiencing an upward trend, according to research by Savills.
Scientists have been able to shed more light on how a dog's wagging tail relates to its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wagged their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans, it's well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just as in humans, the right hemisphere of the brain was responsible for moving the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the sideways tail wagging of their conspecifics, the researchers monitored the animals while they watched films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analysed the behaviour.
We will probably soon understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, "We showed the dogs films of dogs - either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to use them to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog move its tail to the right (as seen from the wagging dog's perspective), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tilt was primarily to the left (again, from the perspective of the dog wagging), their heart rate increased and they looked agitated.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience which movements to worry about and when not to.
He said, "If you have different encounters with other dogs and wagging your tail in one direction tends to be associated with friendly behaviour and the right side tends to produce less friendly behaviour, then you're reacting based on those experiences."
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, vets and trainers better understand their pet's emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behaviour and visiting fellow at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Science, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right matter to dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when it is a happy dog.
Another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada said: "Dogs are more likely to walk towards a robot dog when its 'tail' is wagging to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming agitated - exactly the opposite of the Italian study."
He said the differences could be because the dogs in the different studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs might help, he explained.
"While there is considerable evidence across many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details have yet to be determined - and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
But since their behaviour can be easily recorded, it probably won't be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves one way and sometimes the other.
