Pope Francis will appoint new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time on 22 February, the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who elect a Pope, so Francis will thus appoint the first group of men who will ultimately help choose his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer take part in the papal election - that falls to a group of 120 "cardinals eligible to vote".
