He explained that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as needed to bring the number of eligible cardinals back to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wants.
Next year's consistory is significant because it is the first since Francis was elected in March this year, Valero said.
At present, he said, there is a bit of a surplus on the part of Europe and Italy in particular.
"It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore the balance," he said.
Forty per cent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
