Cry of desperation from an Obama voter
I voted for President Obama twice in hopes that change was possible
He says Obama made laudable efforts that were thwarted by Republican obstructionism
Blockade tactics do not excuse Obamacare website problems, drone strikes
Obama's 2008 campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what might have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a terribly sad book.
It's a book that I thought would cheer me up and give me hope again during my dismal second year of medical school.
It's called The Audacity to Win, and it chronicles Barack Obama's memoir of the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish my patient memoirs in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and speeches could take your breath away.
The election became a landslide and news anchors paused to remind us of the historic significance of the hour.
My classmates wept with joy and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on its way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
Back in 2008, when Obama took office, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a rude awakening, like being jolted out of a dream.
It's hard to remember those optimistic times - they seem a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has indeed changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I recognise the great and varied things Obama has achieved, from passing the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, ending the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and killing Osama bin Laden.
I too believe that partisan obstructionism has overturned too many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and closing Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times to colleagues and acquaintances, I have reached the end of my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain why you allow wiretapping of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers who expose government misconduct are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are being circumvented during presidential elections.
It does not justify the findings of a report that said the White House's efforts to immobilise the media were the "most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration".
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if this is what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that government work might contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, being an MP is not a predictable course, with an opposition party and random events like the Newtown massacre shaping the public debate.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely of the government's own choosing.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and half-baked alternative, he seemed unable to define his direction and positions.
I was under the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfil the hope we had heard about for so long.
But with Obama's approval ratings plummeting to below 45% this week, this book has made the return to 2008 all the harder.
It makes me long for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama took a heavy loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with election officials after the decision, he told his staff they needed to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to find our magic again," he said.
'We need to remember who we are.
It is five years later, Mr President, and I could not agree with you more strongly.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
