Travelling through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr Georges Bwelle brings free medical care to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 "CNN Heroes of 2013".
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to be named "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his ailing father repeatedly lose consciousness and travel to hospitals that did not have the resources to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he only had a broken arm, but then an inflammation formed that spread to his brain, causing a haematoma there that would affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," says Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," Bwelle comments.
You can leave the house at five o'clock in the morning and run to the hospital to be first, and still not be first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organisation.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for 413 people.
But even if there were a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer made Bwelle decide to do something about it.
Dr Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organisation called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and drive over unpaved terrain with the medical equipment strapped to the roof to the villages that need help.
Not everything always goes smoothly.
More than once they have had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a cause for celebration and Bwelle - with his broad smile and boundless energy - is happy to join in the joyous celebration.
The next morning, the team then starts examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from within a 60-kilometre radius of the village - and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides medical care in a range of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document required for school but which many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations with local anaesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, the town hall or a flat; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next one.
The lights for the operating theatre and the disinfection equipment are powered by the group's generator, so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's an exhausting workload, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work," says Bwelle.
Then on Sunday, the team heads back to town, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group - a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students - have performed 700 free surgeries in the last year and know that their work is making a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free hernia surgery he received has now enabled him to return to work.
"This is changing the future of my family," the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon at the hospital, Bwelle also works nights at private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60 % of his charitable work, Bwelle said; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he sleeps," says Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteers with Bwelle's group.
He is always either at the hospital or trying to raise money for the organisation so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe to support Bwelle, it's a chance to get hands-on experience they would never get at home.
"We get to be in surgeries where we help dab blood or hold the instruments for Dr Bwelle," O'Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon and often bring donated medical supplies.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle provides accommodation, transport and guidance.
"He is without a doubt a hero," says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organisation and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives, fulfilling a promise he made to his father, brings him great joy.
"I am so happy when I do this work," Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I am doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
