The Secretary of State also admitted that he shares responsibility with Barack Obama for going on "autopilot" when whistleblower Edward Snowden's explosive revelations about the NSA's spying activities became public.
The leaked information has thrown the US government into a diplomatic storm of outrage from its allies.
In a video-linked speech at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: "Without question, the president and I and others in the government have learned of some things that have gone on virtually on autopilot simply because there was the capability to do so, going back to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, 9/11."
He then became the first senior member of the US government to admit that US spying had crossed a line, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, "In some cases, it has gone unreasonably too far."
The President is determined to bring clarity and is therefore conducting a thorough investigation so that no one need feel that there is abuse here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent people will not be compromised in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force for good and that many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations.
He added: "We are dealing with a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up."
There is a radical extremism in the world that is bent on killing people, blowing themselves up and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept that and stop it before it happens?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the murder of people because we learned of such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, US lawmakers will travel to Europe to allay concerns about alleged American spying and convince Europeans of the need to continue cooperating with the US in anti-terror efforts, the chairman of the Senate European Affairs subcommittee said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to representatives of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in counter-terrorism organisations because of frustration with National Security Agency surveillance.
"It's very important for US national security interests that the Europeans stay on board with our joint efforts against terrorism," Murphy, a first-time Democrat in the Senate who serves as chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations and European Affairs Subcommittee, said in an interview in Washington.
I'm also going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terror, regardless of their anger about the NSA programmes.
Media reports that the NSA collected millions of phone records in Europe have strained relations with some US allies, although the head of intelligence said this week the reports were inaccurate and based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by Nato allies and shared with the United States.
Other revelations quoted from documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA had monitored the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state around the world.
The head of national intelligence, James Clapper, defended spying on allies as necessary, saying it was common practice on both sides.
Amid all the hubbub, Murphy said his agency was preparing for the congressional trip to be held this year and hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other participating MPs are to be released in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary is still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relations, he also spoke of there being some "serious words".
He said European governments needed to be honest with their people about the kind of spying programmes they themselves had been using for years.
"While we can change our surveillance programmes to better protect the rights of Europeans, they also have to come to terms with the fact that we are not the only ones spying," Murphy said.
Meanwhile, John Kerry is scheduled to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to address resentment over US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as US surveillance activities.
Australian woman appeals jail sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney woman sentenced to 15 days in jail in Phuket for falsely claiming she was raped by a taxi driver has appealed the sentence and been released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty of making a false statement by a provincial court in Phuket on 15 June after she told Thai police that a local taxi driver had raped her in the morning hours of Sunday 10 June while two other men held her down.
However, footage from a video camera later showed that she had made it safely to her hotel after being separated from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days until she confessed to making up the story.
She was held in police custody at the scene until the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a low-security detention centre on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than in a prison for adult women.
She is the daughter of Peter Tunks, a former Australian Rubgy League player who has appealed to the Department of Foreign Affairs in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tunks told the Sunday Telegraph in Sydney that the whole family was "extremely concerned" about his daughter's welfare and wanted her back in Australia.
"We're obviously very concerned, but we hope she'll be home as soon as possible," Tunks said.
Bamford has appealed the sentence and is out on 50,000 baht bail.
Australian reports said she was holidaying in the resort of Krabi in southern Thailand in the meantime.
Court sources said Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket and had been warned that the appeal could also lead to the imposition of a higher sentence of up to two years in an adult prison.
However, it is also possible that Thailand could be anxious to improve its tarnished tourist image following the recent murder of travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, and that an acquittal will therefore be handed down.
